               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Gregorian" when="1228" cert="high"><hi rend="italic">c</hi>. 1228 (?)</origDate>
                     <origPlace>
                        <country key="place_1000080">Italy</country>, <placeName key="place_7005139">diocese of Udine</placeName>
                        <!--ORIGINAL: German, Southern Austria-->
                     </origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  
                  <provenance>Presumably written about, or shortly before, 1228, the first year in the calendarial tables on fol. 8r-8v, and certainly after 1200 since the feast of 
                     St Cunigunda (2nd March) is in the Calendar in the original hand. The Calendar points to an origin in the diocese of Aquileia, now Udine. The entry for 9th June 
                     reads 'Consecratio ecclesie monasterii Mosacensis' and this has led to the suggestion that the manuscript was written at the Benedictine abbey of St Gall, Moggio (Mosach). 
                     However, this is a later addition
                   </provenance>
                  
                  <provenance>The Calendar is North Italian with a strong German admixture and has similarities to 
                     <ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_2984">MS. Canon. Liturg. 297</ref>. Compare also:</provenance>
                  
                  <provenance>
                     <list>
                        <item><ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_3032">MS. Canon. Liturg. 35</ref></item>
                        <item><ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_3001">MS. Canon. Liturg. 319</ref></item>
                        <item><ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_3008">MS. Canon. Liturg. 325</ref></item>
                        <item><ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_3022">MS. Canon. Liturg. 340</ref></item>
                        <item><ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_3038">MS. Canon. Liturg. 355</ref></item>
                     </list>
                  </provenance>
                
                  <provenance><persName key="person_2384880" role="fmo">Matteo Luigi Canonici (1727– <hi rend="italic">c</hi>. 1806)</persName></provenance>
                  <provenance notAfter="1807" resp="#SC">Following Canonici's death, the collection passed to his brother, <persName key="person_446" role="fmo">Giuseppe Canonici</persName>, and 
                     then to Canonici's nephew, <persName role="fmo" key="person_431">Giovanni Perissinotti</persName>, in 1807 following Giuseppe Canonici's death</provenance>
